Putin questioned the value of meeting with Zelensky as he considers the Ukraine to be managed by the EU and the US. While not refusing, Putin maintains that he wants to understand what there is to talk about. As perhaps further provocation and an indication of a dislocation of relations between the two countries, the Ukrainian football team for the Euro 2020 tournament has a map of their country including the Crimea that has been annexed by Russia. Official military greetings are used as slogans on the shirt reading reads ‘Glory to Ukraine!’ and ‘Glory to the heroes. It may only be football, but this is a competition showing on the world stage. Russian foreign ministry spokesperson Maria Zakharova has described the slogans as echoing the Nazi rallying cries which is an emotive comment in Russia, https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/857412-ukraine-is-controlled-by-western-leaders-putin

Knowing how fiercely anti-Russian the Ukraine President is, and given the direction the country has taken since 2014, along with Russia still having the upper hand in terms of the geopolitical situation, I doubt that Putin would decide to meet, and I doubt even more that Zelensky would want to see him.

Recalibrating with a lower likelihood of the meeting occurring prior to 01 August (again continuing with the analytical lynchpin that Zelensky would logically seek to meet Biden prior to any meeting with Putin). Zelensky and Biden due to meet at the White House sometime in July. This would leave only two weeks to cement logistics for the Zelensky and Putin meeting subsequent to the White House visit - indicating it increasing unlikely that a meeting between Zelensky and Putin will occur prior to the cut-off date.

Ukraine appear to be "choosing their side" in the face of some fairly ludicrous conditions for meeting from the Russian side: a move that will certainly annoy Putin who will only want to meet with his Ukranian counterpart from a position of strength.
It would seem that Moscow sets insuperable preconditions to meeting with Zelensky, which I cannot see how the latter could navigate before August 1.

The Nord Stream 2 pipeline seems to be well underway. Russia and Germany have ties between this. Russia and Germany also had ties with the Navalny extredition. Germany is going through a federal election and the leader will be decided in September. At that time would be a perfect opportunity to have a Normandy style meeting between Germany, France, Russia, and Ukraine, as proposed. Now if that also means it could happen sooner as a last get-together with German Chancellor Angela Merkel, that's also possible.
Revising upward. There are a number of issues still to be discussed.

Favoring a meeting by a hair now, I'm seeing news articles talking about a "Normandy Format" meeting, which is apparently a meeting between the leaders of France, Germany, Russia, and Ukraine. I'll update more in the next week if more mainstream coverage of the possibility starts happening. A big question is even if they do this meeting if it will be scheduled before August 1.

After finding a recent article on the pre-conditions made by the Kremlin in regards to a Putin-Zelensky meeting, I've lowered my probability of them meeting by August 1. While public rhetoric and private discussions can greatly differ, it doesn't seem likely that Zelensky will adhere to the demands. Furthermore, with June 16 as the date for the Biden-Putin meeting there is a chance I guess that it could happen after that, but until a US ambassador to Ukraine is appointed, I don't think the US is giving a very encouraging vibe. And I don't see another force that could really push the two to engage, but I could be wrong.

France's Macron quoted: "We have agreed with Russian President Vladimir Putin, with whom we spoke several weeks ago, and with Ukrainian President Vladimir Zelensky, with whom we also spoke, to arrange a ministerial-level discussion." Source: https://tass.com/world/1296381

EDIT: "Speaking with Italian newspaper La Repubblica, Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky said that he believes the Vatican could be the best place for a meeting with Russian President Vladimir Putin. 'Yes, perhaps, this could be the best place from all points of view. The Vatican is truly an ideal place for dialogue about peace. The Holy See is a global moral authority that always acts effectively as a mediator, as it is impartial and it inspires trust among all parties to the conflict. That is why the Apostolic Capital has often been used in history to resolve conflicts between states and build a peaceful future,' Zelensky said." https://angelusnews.com/news/world/how-realistic-is-the-idea-of-russia-ukraine-peace-talks-at-the-vatican/

Recent developments in the Russian supplied Nord Stream 2 pipeline to Germany have sparked renewed interest in a Putin/Zelensky meeting. The US is advocating against the deal, as it would bypass Ukraine and undermine European security. However, an olive branch of eased sanctions for the pipeline's CEO (a German) is in the works, as it could possibly dampen Russian reliance on Chinese investment. In my assessment, it "could" open the door for a meeting, if Germany or Europe were to put stipulations on Russia to acknowledge Ukrainian sovereignty before the gas turns on. Either way, the Russia/China/US triangle poses an interesting conundrum with Ukraine and Taiwan in similar "monkey in the middle" situations, likely to be made only more prominent as the Beijing-Kremlin relationship grows.

There appears to be no movement on a Putin and Zelensky meeting, and with only vague assurances from the US, the chances of a meeting are slimmer. However, the strategic goals of Ukraine remain clear: attain a membership action plan from NATO and thus join the EU. Any concrete movement toward NATO would likely set off a hostile Russian response, and provoke some sort of action from NATO. Yet, many EU nations are apprehensive about permitting a nation into the group under tense conditions. I don't think NATO desires a true confrontation with Russia and thus the meeting will likely not take place because no one will be forcing it.

US is planning for a US-Russia summit this summer and the US president may also meet the Ukraine president during his Europe visit. Hence, there are chances that Ukraine may be in the agenda. If Russia agrees to include Ukraine in the agenda, then there is a possibility of high-level meetings leading to a presidential summit. All these series of events, if they happen, will take a long time and August is too short to see this.

Given current tensions & statements from both sides a meeting before the (still unconfirmed) US and Russian premier's bilateral seems incredibly unlikely despite Putin's claim that he' be happy to meet "any time" [1 and 2]. No signs of agenda agreement which seemed to be key to Zelensky's major achievements the last time these two met [3].
I believe it is highly unlikely that such a meeting will occur prior to 01 August.

It seems as though both sides desire a meeting, but for different reasons. On Russia's behalf it's likely just for overtures in order to ease sanctions, while Ukraine seeks recognizable actions towards lowering tension. If they do meet, it will likely not be before August, and it will not be in Russia or Ukraine, but rather someplace mutually acceptable, without the possibility of external influence.

As @Ryan-Beck points out, there is evidence that Putin is willing to be diplomatic by the withdrawal of Russian troops. Then you factor in the fact that Biden and Putin are in the works of setting up a meeting this summer, given that both seem to be okay with the meeting taking place. Thus, there is a reasonable probability that Putin rides a wave of diplomatic meetings this summer and perhaps by August 1, 2021 - the closing date for this question.

It seems like there's interest on both sides so I think there's decent weight on the possibility of a meeting, and Putin withdrawing troops makes it seem like willingness to be diplomatic may be real.

The first questions to ask here is who would benefit from such a meeting and what is the end game. Zelensky has suggested that he and Putin meet in Eastern Ukraine. Apart form the security issues, Putin holds the upper hand and would not acquiesce to such an arrangement. Putin has stated that Volodymyr Zelensky is welcome in Moscow at any time, to discuss bilateral relations, but concerning the fighting in the Donbas region, the Ukrainian President should first discuss the conflict with Denis Pushilin and Leonid Pasechnik who are the leaders of the two breakaway republics, Donetsk and Lugansk, to then discuss with third parties such as Russia. This is somewhat disingenuous as Russia still considers the Ukraine to be a region rather than a sovereign country as it was one of the most important republics of the Soviet Union.

To be honest I doubt he will make any progress on ending the war as yesterday’s news underscored that the Kremlin is simply not interested as the conflict guarantees Ukraine can never join NATO, which can’t accept new members with an active border dispute according to its charter. Zelenskiy offered direct talks with Putin on Donbas and wants to revise the Minsk II deal. Putin stuck to the fiction that Russia is an impartial observer (this point is enshrined in the Minsk II protocols) and that Zelenskiy needs to resolve the conflict with the rebel leaders in Donbas, not the Kremlin, but if he wants to go to Moscow for talks on improving bilateral relations he is welcome. This isn’t going anywhere any time soon. bne news
